<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="44.[264,1321,284,430]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis box="[312,414,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Remarks</emphasis>
: Both 
<taxonomicName box="[495,593,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varna">
<emphasis box="[495,593,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">S. varna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[652,804,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolorata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[652,804,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">S. bicolorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[812,903,284,310]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resemble each other externally and have very distinctive coloration. They also share the compressed aedeagus and the slender elongate needlelike paraphyses. 
<taxonomicName box="[648,747,364,389]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varna">
<emphasis box="[648,747,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">S. varna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not bear any process on the aedeagal shaft whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[367,489,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolorata">
<emphasis box="[367,489,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">bicolorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a pair of slender, elongate, apical processes.
</paragraph>
